on for its examples of virtue. Employing the same philosophy, Sidney, in his letter to Queen Elizabeth and in his fiction, arrogates to himself the role of court counsellor. Robert Devereux also draws, Wood argues, on the optimistic and conciliatory philosophy signified by Sidney’s New Arcadia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArcadia in literaturexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophyxHistoryy16th century. 0aPastoral literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aProtestantism and literaturexHistoryy16th century. 0aVirtue in literature. 4aShakespeare 2020. 70(DE-588)4194426-40(DE-627)1052196060(DE-576)210094052aTugendgMotiv2gnd 70(DE-588)4725426-90(DE-627)3658290130(DE-576)215211766aPhilippisten2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAnti-factionalism.  aArcadia.  aCounsel.  aEssex.  aHeliodorus.  aMelanchthon.  aNeostoicism.  aPhilippism.  aRomance.  aSidney.1 aWood, Richard James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613647340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526136473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526136473/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles